Ask HN: What's Up with the Metaverse?
text:
From the outside it looks like a joke -- nobody is using it as far as I can tell, it's costing Meta exorbitant amounts of money and not least: it looks like tech that would have been unimpressive 10 years ago.

I don't get it and I feel like there must be something I am missing. Mark Zuckerberg, in spite of what I might otherwise think of him, always appeared to be an extraordinary strategist. And if there is anything Meta does well, it's engineering! So are we just seeing the first clumsy iteration of something that will truly change the world? Or are they simply experiencing their Google Wave/Plus/... moment? I am genuinely curious!

Ask HN: How did you learn to draw diagrams?
text:
I find myself getting into more situations where I have to convey the structure of a project, or the workflow of a functionality, or a general idea for a UI, and I have very limited skills at what I can produce. I can usually get by with simple diagrams and meetings to clarify the rest, but it would be nice to produce more expressive diagrams to convey more complex ideas.

Do you know any books or articles or software that have helped you develop these skills? Did you learn to draw diagrams for different scenarios (databases, networks, UI, workflows), or do the skills in one scenario translate easily to others?

Currently I usually get stuck into one of the following approaches:

- UML, but I find that you almost never want the whole database on screen when discussing something, and to show only parts of the database UML is not so descriptive to highlight the different functionalities.

- Boxes and arrows. I always find that colored boxes and arrows work well for 3-4 components, but start getting mushy after that and I need more resources to be able to convey different levels of abstraction.

Ask HN: Why not have jackets warn you when they are unsuitable for the weather?
text:
A jacket (and other clothing) could have access to today's weather report and warn you when you put it on whenever it is inappropriate for today's weather.

If you don't wear a jacket but you should, then your t-shirt could warn you that it is not enough without a jacket for today's weather.

Ask HN: Ok, Who Works at Bungie?
text:
I'm asking this here because it seems like there arent any good search results for this question, but I swear I saw some bungie commentors on here in the past.

I have a friend who constantly gets exotics (approximately 1 per hour playing heroic nightfalls) in Destiny 2. Another friend and I have never had one drop (only given in storyline/quests rewards) after 50+ hours of play, including playing dungeons and nightfalls with this other friend.

I'm wondering if there are individusl player factors that heavily weight drop rate... or if the universe just hates some people more (aka how can a randomization algo sustain these sorts of streaks without individual player factors)?
